161 344 M 
-0.200 0 ( Description:)A 
; : 161 389 1500 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 389 M 
-0.200 0 (         There is a small omission in the description of the)A 
; : 161 434 1925 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 434 M 
-0.200 0 (         constant-expression which is used to set an enumerator's value, e.g.)A 
; : 161 524 1500 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 524 M 
-0.200 0 (             enum A { a, b = a + 2 \);  // expression "a + 2")A 
; : 161 614 1825 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 614 M 
-0.200 0 (         The type of "a" in "a+2" presumably follows the usual expression)A 
; : 161 659 1175 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 659 M 
-0.200 0 (         rules.  But these rules say, in 4.5/2:)A 
; : 161 749 1950 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 749 M 
-0.200 0 (            An rvalue of type wchar_t \(3.9.1\) or an enumeration type \(7.2\) can)A 
; : 161 794 1950 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 794 M 
-0.200 0 (            be converted to an rvalue of the first of the following types that)A 
; : 161 839 1725 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 839 M 
-0.200 0 (            can represent all the values of its underlying type: int,)A 
; : 161 884 1225 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 884 M 
-0.200 0 (            unsigned int, long, or unsigned long.)A 
; : 161 974 1850 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 974 M 
-0.200 0 (         So the evaluation of "a+2" depends on the underlying type of "A",)A 
; : 161 1019 1950 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1019 M 
-0.200 0 (         which in turn depends on the value of "b", which depends on the value)A 
; : 161 1064 450 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1064 M 
-0.200 0 (         of "a+2".)A 
; : 161 1154 1850 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1154 M 
-0.200 0 (         Although this is unlikely to affect real programs in practice, we)A 
; : 161 1199 1900 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1199 M 
-0.200 0 (         should fix the definition.  There are cases where it matters, e.g.:)A 
; : 161 1289 1750 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1289 M 
-0.200 0 (             // Assume an environment where "int" is 16 bits, just for)A 
; : 161 1334 1850 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1334 M 
-0.200 0 (             // convenience \(The same problem occurs when "int" is larger.)A 
; : 161 1379 1800 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1379 M 
-0.200 0 (             // Think of systems where "int" is 32 bits and "long" is 64)A 
; : 161 1424 550 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1424 M 
-0.200 0 (             // bits.\))A 
; : 161 1514 1275 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1514 M 
-0.200 0 (             enum A { a = 1, b = a-2, c = 32768U };)A 
; : 161 1604 1925 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1604 M 
-0.200 0 (         If we assume the underlying type will be "int", then b is -1 and the)A 
; : 161 1649 1050 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1649 M 
-0.200 0 (         actual underlying type is "long".)A 
; : 161 1739 1875 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1739 M 
-0.200 0 (         If we assume the underlying type will be "unsigned int", then b is)A 
; : 161 1784 1600 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1784 M 
-0.200 0 (         65535 and the actual underlying type is "unsigned int".)A 
; : 161 1874 1275 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
161 1874 M 
-0.200 0 (         The answer may seem obvious, but consider:)A 
; : 161 1964 1200 45 rc 0 0 0 sco F0_42
Ji 
